Note: ================================================================
Note: LaTeX to HIR Translator
Note: ================================================================
Note: Translates LaTeX AST to HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation).
Note: Handles document structure, math mode, formatting, and cross-references.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_parser.runa" as LaTeXParser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

Note: ================================================================
Note: LaTeX-specific HIR Node Types
Note: ================================================================
Note: These extend the HIR with LaTeX-specific constructs

Constant HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT as Integer is 5000
Constant HIR_LATEX_SECTION as Integer is 5001
Constant HIR_LATEX_SUBSECTION as Integer is 5002
Constant HIR_LATEX_SUBSUBSECTION as Integer is 5003
Constant HIR_LATEX_PARAGRAPH as Integer is 5004
Constant HIR_LATEX_SUBPARAGRAPH as Integer is 5005

Constant HIR_LATEX_ENVIRONMENT as Integer is 5010
Constant HIR_LATEX_ITEMIZE as Integer is 5011
Constant HIR_LATEX_ENUMERATE as Integer is 5012
Constant HIR_LATEX_DESCRIPTION as Integer is 5013
Constant HIR_LATEX_FIGURE as Integer is 5014
Constant HIR_LATEX_TABLE as Integer is 5015
Constant HIR_LATEX_EQUATION as Integer is 5016

Constant HIR_LATEX_TEXT_BOLD as Integer is 5020
Constant HIR_LATEX_TEXT_ITALIC as Integer is 5021
Constant HIR_LATEX_TEXT_EMPH as Integer is 5022
Constant HIR_LATEX_TEXT_UNDERLINE as Integer is 5023
Constant HIR_LATEX_TEXT_TYPEWRITER as Integer is 5024

Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_INLINE as Integer is 5030
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_DISPLAY as Integer is 5031
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_FRAC as Integer is 5032
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_SQRT as Integer is 5033
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUM as Integer is 5034
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_INT as Integer is 5035
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_PROD as Integer is 5036
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_LIMIT as Integer is 5037
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUPERSCRIPT as Integer is 5038
Constant HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUBSCRIPT as Integer is 5039

Constant HIR_LATEX_CITATION as Integer is 5040
Constant HIR_LATEX_REFERENCE as Integer is 5041
Constant HIR_LATEX_LABEL as Integer is 5042
Constant HIR_LATEX_PAGEREF as Integer is 5043

Constant HIR_LATEX_PREAMBLE as Integer is 5050
Constant HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS as Integer is 5051
Constant HIR_LATEX_USEPACKAGE as Integer is 5052

Note: ================================================================
Note: Translator State
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translator state for the LaTeX-to-HIR frontend. Holds the HIR module
being constructed, separate diagnostic lists (errors and warnings),
a scope stack for nested environment tracking, and tables of label
and citation references for cross-reference validation in a final
pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
48-byte record (6 x i64). Offsets: 0 hir_module, 8 errors list, 16
warnings list, 24 current_scope stack, 32 label_table, 40
citation_table. All lists are ListCore handles. Created by
create_translator.
@End Implementation
Type called "LaTeXTranslator":
    hir_module as Integer
    errors as Integer
    warnings as Integer
    current_scope as Integer
    label_table as Integer
    citation_table as Integer
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Translator Creation and Initialization
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Creates and primes a LaTeXTranslator. Initialises the HIR module
root as a HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT and the five auxiliary lists so the
first call to translate has all needed slots populated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Memory.allocate(48). Creates a 32-byte HIR module with type
HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT, name "latex_document", and an empty items list
at offset 16. Stores the module pointer at translator offset 0.
Allocates ListCore lists for errors (8), warnings (16), scope_stack
(24), label_table (32), citation_table (40). Returns the translator
handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_translator" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Let translator_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 48

    Note: Create empty HIR module
    Let module_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with module_ptr, 0, HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT
    proc write_string from Memory with module_ptr, 8, "latex_document"
    Let items_list be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with module_ptr, 16, items_list

    proc write_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 0, module_ptr

    Note: Initialize error and warning lists
    Let errors_list be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 8, errors_list

    Let warnings_list be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 16, warnings_list

    Note: Initialize scope stack (for nested environments)
    Let scope_stack be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 24, scope_stack

    Note: Initialize label table (for \label tracking)
    Let label_table be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 32, label_table

    Note: Initialize citation table (for \cite tracking)
    Let citation_table be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 40, citation_table

    Return translator_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Main Translation Entry Point
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry. Validates the AST root is a NODE_DOCUMENT then
dispatches to the preamble and body translators. The returned value
is the populated HIR module handle.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null AST guard: emits "Null AST" error and returns 0. Reads root
type at offset 0; if not LaTeXParser.NODE_DOCUMENT emits "Expected
DOCUMENT" error. Reads preamble (offset 8); if non-null calls
translate_preamble. Reads body (offset 16); if non-null calls
translate_content_list. Returns the HIR module from offset 0 of
translator.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, latex_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If latex_ast is equal to 0:
        proc add_error with translator_ptr, "Null AST provided to translator"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with latex_ast, 0

    If node_type is not equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_DOCUMENT:
        proc add_error with translator_ptr, "Expected DOCUMENT node at AST root"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Translate preamble
    Let preamble_ptr be proc read_integer from Memory with latex_ast, 8
    If preamble_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_preamble with translator_ptr, preamble_ptr
    End If

    Note: Translate document body
    Let body_ptr be proc read_integer from Memory with latex_ast, 16
    If body_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc translate_content_list with translator_ptr, body_ptr
    End If

    Let module_ptr be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 0
    Return module_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Preamble Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Iterates the preamble items (\documentclass, \usepackage, custom
preamble commands) and emits HIR for each. The preamble ends at
\begin{document}; the parser separates it from the body so this
translator never accidentally consumes body nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Type-checks the preamble node. Reads the items list from offset 8;
loops 0..size calling translate_preamble_item for each. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_preamble" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, preamble_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with preamble_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_PREAMBLE:
        proc add_error with translator_ptr, "Expected PREAMBLE node"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let items_list be proc read_integer from Memory with preamble_ptr, 8
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with items_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let item_ptr be proc get_from_list from ListCore with items_list, index
        proc translate_preamble_item with translator_ptr, item_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches a single preamble item by its parser-assigned kind:
\documentclass, \usepackage, or a generic preamble command. Unknown
preamble kinds return 0 silently so HIR construction is robust to
parser-extension nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads node_type at offset 0. Cascade: NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS ->
translate_documentclass; NODE_USEPACKAGE -> translate_usepackage;
NODE_COMMAND -> translate_preamble_command. Falls through to 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_preamble_item" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, item_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS:
        Return proc translate_documentclass with translator_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise:
        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_USEPACKAGE:

            Return proc translate_usepackage with translator_ptr, item_ptr
        Otherwise:
            If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_COMMAND:

                Return proc translate_preamble_command with translator_ptr, item_ptr
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits HIR for '\documentclass[options]{class}'. The class name comes
from the required argument and options from the optional bracket
argument; both are captured as strings on the resulting
HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte node with type HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS. Reads
the required arg (offset 8) and extracts its text into the name slot.
Reads the optional arg (offset 16); if non-null extracts text into
the options slot, otherwise stores empty string. Adds to module.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_documentclass" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, docclass_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR node for document class
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS

    Note: Extract class name from required argument
    Let class_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with docclass_ptr, 8
    Let class_name be proc extract_text_from_argument from class_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, class_name

    Note: Extract options from optional argument
    Let options_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with docclass_ptr, 16
    Let options_str be ""
    If options_arg is not equal to 0:
        Set options_str to proc extract_text_from_argument from options_arg
    End If
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 16, options_str

    Note: Add to module items
    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
LaTeX `\usepackage[opts]{name}` declarations are the document's analogue
of imports - they pull in macro definitions and styling from external
packages. We capture both the package name (offset 8 of the parser node)
and the optional [options] argument (offset 16) so downstream HIR
consumers can decide which packages map to which target-format
equivalents (e.g., `graphicx` -> include-image support, `hyperref` ->
link generation).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node. Writes HIR_LATEX_USEPACKAGE at offset 0.
Reads package_arg from parser offset 8, extracts the text via
extract_text_from_argument, writes it at HIR offset 8. Reads options_arg
from parser offset 16; if non-zero extracts its text into options_str,
otherwise leaves "". Writes options_str at HIR offset 16. Calls
add_to_module to enroll the node. Returns 1 (success).
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_usepackage" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, package_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR node for package import
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_USEPACKAGE

    Note: Extract package name
    Let package_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with package_ptr, 8
    Let package_name be proc extract_text_from_argument from package_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, package_name

    Note: Extract options
    Let options_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with package_ptr, 16
    Let options_str be ""
    If options_arg is not equal to 0:
        Set options_str to proc extract_text_from_argument from options_arg
    End If
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 16, options_str

    Note: Add to module items
    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preamble commands like `\title`, `\author`, `\date` set document
metadata that doesn't render at the call site but flows into
`\maketitle`. We tag them HIR_METADATA (rather than HIR_CALL) so
downstream passes know to route them to the document-info table
instead of inline output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads command_name from parser offset 8. Allocates a 40-byte HIR node
tagged HIR.HIR_METADATA. Writes command_name at HIR offset 8. Reads
args_list from parser offset 16 and translates it via
translate_argument_list, writing the resulting HIR list at offset 16.
Calls add_to_module. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_preamble_command" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, command_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Handle preamble commands like \title, \author, \date
    Let command_name be proc read_string from Memory with command_ptr, 8

    Note: Create generic command HIR node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 40
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR.HIR_METADATA
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, command_name

    Note: Translate arguments
    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with command_ptr, 16
    Let hir_args be proc translate_argument_list with translator_ptr, args_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, hir_args

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Content Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Iterates a parser List of content nodes (section bodies, environment
bodies, top-level document content) and dispatches each through
translate_node. Side-effects-only: each translation enrolls its HIR
node into the module via add_to_module, so this helper itself doesn't
need to return individual results.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads count via ListCore.get_list_size(content_list). Initialises
index = 0. Loops while index < count: reads node_ptr at index via
ListCore.get_from_list, calls translate_node(translator_ptr, node_ptr),
bumps index. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_content_list" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, content_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
        proc translate_node with translator_ptr, node_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
LaTeX-AST dispatcher that routes each parser node to its specialised
HIR translator based on the node_type tag stored at offset 0. The
node_type set covers LaTeX's syntactic categories: sectioning commands
(SECTION/SUBSECTION/etc), ENVIRONMENT, COMMAND, TEXT_BLOCK, MATH_INLINE
and MATH_DISPLAY, CITATION, REFERENCE, LABEL, LIST_ITEM. Unrecognised
types fall through to Return 0 (the translation simply produces no HIR
for unknown constructs - this is safer than aborting because LaTeX
documents commonly have package-specific macros we can't handle).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards node_ptr (returns 0). Reads node_type at offset 0. A long
cascading-If chain compares node_type against LaTeXParser node-type
constants and tail-calls the matching translator: NODE_SECTION /
SUBSECTION / SUBSUBSECTION / PARAGRAPH / SUBPARAGRAPH -> translate_section
with the corresponding HIR_LATEX_* type tag; NODE_ENVIRONMENT ->
translate_environment; NODE_COMMAND -> translate_command; NODE_TEXT_BLOCK
-> translate_text_block; NODE_MATH_INLINE/DISPLAY -> translate_math_*;
NODE_CITATION -> translate_citation; NODE_REFERENCE -> translate_reference;
NODE_LABEL -> translate_label; NODE_LIST_ITEM -> translate_list_item.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_node" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with node_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_SECTION:
        Return proc translate_section with translator_ptr, node_ptr, HIR_LATEX_SECTION
    Otherwise:
        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_SUBSECTION:

            Return proc translate_section with translator_ptr, node_ptr, HIR_LATEX_SUBSECTION
        Otherwise:
            If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_SUBSUBSECTION:

                Return proc translate_section with translator_ptr, node_ptr, HIR_LATEX_SUBSUBSECTION
            Otherwise:
                If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_PARAGRAPH:

                    Return proc translate_section with translator_ptr, node_ptr, HIR_LATEX_PARAGRAPH
                Otherwise:
                    If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_SUBPARAGRAPH:

                        Return proc translate_section with translator_ptr, node_ptr, HIR_LATEX_SUBPARAGRAPH
                    Otherwise:
                        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_ENVIRONMENT:

                            Return proc translate_environment with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                        Otherwise:
                            If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_COMMAND:

                                Return proc translate_command with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                            Otherwise:
                                If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_TEXT_BLOCK:

                                    Return proc translate_text_block with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                Otherwise:
                                    If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_MATH_INLINE:

                                        Return proc translate_math_inline with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                    Otherwise:
                                        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_MATH_DISPLAY:

                                            Return proc translate_math_display with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                        Otherwise:
                                            If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_CITATION:

                                                Return proc translate_citation with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                            Otherwise:
                                                If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_REFERENCE:

                                                    Return proc translate_reference with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                                Otherwise:
                                                    If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_LABEL:

                                                        Return proc translate_label with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                                    Otherwise:
                                                        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_LIST_ITEM:

                                                            Return proc translate_list_item with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                                                        End If
                                                    End If
                                                End If
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Unknown node type - add warning
    Let warning_msg be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Unknown node type: ", proc string_from_integer from StringCore with node_type
    proc add_warning with translator_ptr, warning_msg

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Section Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Shared translator for all five LaTeX sectioning levels (section,
subsection, subsubsection, paragraph, subparagraph) - they share
identical structure but produce different HIR types. Three fields:
title (required, the visible heading text), short_title (optional,
used in TOC entries), and content (the body of the section, a list of
child nodes). Children are recursively translated through translate_node
so nested constructs (e.g., subsection inside section) get their own
HIR nodes appended to the content list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 40-byte HIR node, tags it with the passed hir_type
parameter. Extracts title_arg from parser offset 8, runs
extract_text_from_argument, writes title_text at HIR offset 8. Extracts
optional short_title_arg from parser offset 16; if non-zero extracts
its text into short_title (otherwise ""), writes at HIR offset 16.
Reads content_list at parser offset 24, creates a fresh ListCore list
hir_content. If content_list is non-zero, loops content_list translating
each child via translate_node and appending non-zero results to
hir_content. Writes hir_content at HIR offset 24. Calls add_to_module.
Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_section" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, section_ptr as Integer, hir_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR section node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 40
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, hir_type

    Note: Extract section title
    Let title_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 8
    Let title_text be proc extract_text_from_argument from title_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, title_text

    Note: Extract optional short title
    Let short_title_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 16
    Let short_title be ""
    If short_title_arg is not equal to 0:
        Set short_title to proc extract_text_from_argument from short_title_arg
    End If
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 16, short_title

    Note: Translate section content
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 24
    Let hir_content be proc create_list from ListCore

    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let content_node be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
            Let hir_content_node be proc translate_node with translator_ptr, content_node
            If hir_content_node is not equal to 0:
                proc add_to_list from ListCore with hir_content, hir_content_node
            End If
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 24, hir_content

    Note: Add to module items
    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Environment Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
LaTeX environments (`\begin{name}...\end{name}`) cover everything from
itemize/enumerate lists to figures/tables to equations to bare custom
environments. We dispatch to get_environment_hir_type to map well-
known names to specialised HIR_LATEX_* tags (ITEMIZE, ENUMERATE,
FIGURE, TABLE, EQUATION) so downstream backends emit format-native
output, with HIR_LATEX_ENVIRONMENT as the generic fallback. The
environment's parameters (e.g. `\begin{figure}[h!]`) are preserved
as a free-form string for the backend to interpret.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads name_arg from parser offset 8, extracts env_name. Calls
get_environment_hir_type(env_name) to choose a specialised HIR tag.
Allocates a 48-byte HIR node tagged with the chosen type, writes
env_name at offset 8. Reads params_arg at parser offset 16; if non-zero
extracts text into params_str (else ""), writes at HIR offset 16.
Reads content_list at parser offset 24, builds hir_content by looping
each child through translate_node and appending non-zero results.
Writes hir_content at HIR offset 24. Calls add_to_module. Returns
hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_environment" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, env_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extract environment name
    Let name_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 8
    Let env_name be proc extract_text_from_argument from name_arg

    Note: Determine HIR type based on environment name
    Let hir_type be proc get_environment_hir_type from env_name

    Note: Create HIR environment node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 48
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, hir_type
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, env_name

    Note: Translate optional parameters
    Let params_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 16
    Let params_str be ""
    If params_arg is not equal to 0:
        Set params_str to proc extract_text_from_argument from params_arg
    End If
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 16, params_str

    Note: Translate environment content
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 24
    Let hir_content be proc create_list from ListCore

    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let content_node be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
            Let hir_content_node be proc translate_node with translator_ptr, content_node
            If hir_content_node is not equal to 0:
                proc add_to_list from ListCore with hir_content, hir_content_node
            End If
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 24, hir_content

    Note: Add to module items
    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
String-keyed lookup that maps well-known LaTeX environment names to
their specialised HIR type constants. We use direct string_equals
chains rather than a hash table because the set is small (7 names) and
the chain ends in a generic-fallback Return that costs nothing extra.
The three math environments (equation, align, gather) collapse to a
single HIR_LATEX_EQUATION because all three are visually equivalent at
the HIR level - the alignment-specific layout is handled by math-
backend rendering, not by separate HIR types.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Cascade of string_equals tests via StringCore: "itemize" ->
HIR_LATEX_ITEMIZE, "enumerate" -> HIR_LATEX_ENUMERATE, "description"
-> HIR_LATEX_DESCRIPTION, "figure" -> HIR_LATEX_FIGURE, "table" ->
HIR_LATEX_TABLE, "equation"/"align"/"gather" all -> HIR_LATEX_EQUATION.
Falls through to Return HIR_LATEX_ENVIRONMENT for any unknown name.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_environment_hir_type" that takes env_name as String returns Integer:
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "itemize":
        Return HIR_LATEX_ITEMIZE
    Otherwise:
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "enumerate":

            Return HIR_LATEX_ENUMERATE
        Otherwise:
            If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "description":

                Return HIR_LATEX_DESCRIPTION
            Otherwise:
                If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "figure":

                    Return HIR_LATEX_FIGURE
                Otherwise:
                    If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "table":

                        Return HIR_LATEX_TABLE
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "equation":

                            Return HIR_LATEX_EQUATION
                        Otherwise:
                            If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "align":

                                Return HIR_LATEX_EQUATION
                            Otherwise:
                                If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "gather":

                                    Return HIR_LATEX_EQUATION
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Generic environment
    Return HIR_LATEX_ENVIRONMENT
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Command Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level command dispatcher with two layers: first checks for well-
known text-formatting commands (`\textbf`, `\textit`, `\emph`,
`\underline`, `\texttt`) and routes to translate_text_format with a
specific HIR type for each; second falls through to a generic
HIR.HIR_CALL representation for any other command. Text-formatting
commands get their own HIR types because backends typically need to
emit different markup (`<b>` vs `<i>` vs `<em>` in HTML, `**` vs `*`
in Markdown) - whereas generic `\command{args}` just becomes a call
node the backend can pattern-match on name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads command_name from parser offset 8. Sequence of string_equals
tests against "\\textbf"/"\\textit"/"\\emph"/"\\underline"/"\\texttt",
each tail-calling translate_text_format with HIR_LATEX_TEXT_BOLD/ITALIC/
EMPH/UNDERLINE/TYPEWRITER respectively. Fallthrough: allocates a 40-byte
HIR node tagged HIR.HIR_CALL with command_name at offset 8. Reads
args_list at parser offset 16, calls translate_argument_list, writes
hir_args at offset 16. Calls add_to_module. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_command" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, command_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let command_name be proc read_string from Memory with command_ptr, 8

    Note: Check for text formatting commands
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\textbf":
        Return proc translate_text_format with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_TEXT_BOLD
    Otherwise:
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\textit":

            Return proc translate_text_format with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_TEXT_ITALIC
        Otherwise:
            If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\emph":

                Return proc translate_text_format with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_TEXT_EMPH
            Otherwise:
                If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\underline":

                    Return proc translate_text_format with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_TEXT_UNDERLINE
                Otherwise:
                    If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\texttt":

                        Return proc translate_text_format with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_TEXT_TYPEWRITER
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Generic command translation
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 40
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR.HIR_CALL
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, command_name

    Note: Translate arguments
    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with command_ptr, 16
    Let hir_args be proc translate_argument_list with translator_ptr, args_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, hir_args

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shared helper for all text-formatting commands. Two-channel storage:
the plain text (for backends that can render the formatting inline
on a string) AND the recursive nested HIR content (for backends that
need to walk nested formatting like `\textbf{hello \emph{world}}`).
Storing both costs little extra memory and saves a re-translation
pass when the backend changes strategy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged with the passed hir_type. Reads
args_list from parser offset 16, gets first_arg via
ListCore.get_from_list at index 0. Extracts text via
extract_text_from_argument and writes it at HIR offset 8. Then calls
translate_argument_content(translator_ptr, first_arg) to produce the
nested HIR tree and writes it at HIR offset 16. Calls add_to_module.
Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_text_format" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, command_ptr as Integer, hir_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR text formatting node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, hir_type

    Note: Extract formatted text from first argument
    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with command_ptr, 16
    Let first_arg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, 0
    Let text_content be proc extract_text_from_argument from first_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, text_content

    Note: Store nested content if complex
    Let nested_content be proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, first_arg
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, nested_content

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Math Mode Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inline math (`$...$` or `\(...\)`) flows within prose at character
level - the HIR_LATEX_MATH_INLINE tag distinguishes it from display
math because backends typically use different markup (e.g., MathML
`<math display="inline">` vs `<math display="block">`).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_MATH_INLINE. Reads
content_list from parser offset 8, calls
translate_math_content(translator_ptr, content_list) to produce a
recursive HIR list of math nodes. Writes the list at HIR offset 8.
Calls add_to_module. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_inline" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, math_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR inline math node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_MATH_INLINE

    Note: Translate math content
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 8
    Let hir_content be proc translate_math_content with translator_ptr, content_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, hir_content

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Display math (`$$...$$`, `\[...\]`, `equation`, `align`) renders as a
centered block on its own line - structurally identical at HIR level
to inline math, with only the type tag (HIR_LATEX_MATH_DISPLAY)
distinguishing them. Same content shape so a single math-content
walker handles both.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_MATH_DISPLAY. Reads
content_list from parser offset 8, calls translate_math_content to
produce recursive HIR. Writes the list at HIR offset 8. Calls
add_to_module. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_display" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, math_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR display math node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_MATH_DISPLAY

    Note: Translate math content
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 8
    Let hir_content be proc translate_math_content with translator_ptr, content_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, hir_content

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Math content has its own dispatcher distinct from text content because
the same parser-node types behave differently in math mode: a NODE_COMMAND
in math context might be `\frac` (translate_math_frac) while in text it
would be a generic `\command`. Returning a List of translated nodes
lets callers iterate or serialise as a sequence.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates empty hir_content_list. If content_list is null, returns the
empty list. Otherwise loops index 0 to count-1: reads node_ptr via
ListCore.get_from_list, calls translate_math_node (NOT translate_node)
on it, appends non-zero results to hir_content_list. Returns
hir_content_list.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_content" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, content_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir_content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    If content_list is equal to 0:
        Return hir_content_list
    End If

    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
        Let hir_node be proc translate_math_node with translator_ptr, node_ptr

        If hir_node is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list from ListCore with hir_content_list, hir_node
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_content_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Math-mode-specific dispatcher: branches on parser node_type to route
commands to translate_math_command (which knows the math-mode command
semantics), text blocks to translate_math_text (which treats them as
identifier-typed variables/symbols rather than literal text), and
super/subscript nodes to their specialised translators. Falls through
to the general translate_node for unrecognised types, ensuring nested
math constructs never get silently dropped.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards node_ptr. Reads node_type at offset 0. Dispatches:
NODE_COMMAND -> translate_math_command; NODE_TEXT_BLOCK ->
translate_math_text; NODE_MATH_SUPERSCRIPT -> translate_math_superscript;
NODE_MATH_SUBSCRIPT -> translate_math_subscript. Default returns
translate_node(translator_ptr, node_ptr) as the catch-all.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_node" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with node_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_COMMAND:
        Return proc translate_math_command with translator_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise:
        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_TEXT_BLOCK:

            Note: Math symbols and variables
            Return proc translate_math_text with translator_ptr, node_ptr
        Otherwise:
            If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_MATH_SUPERSCRIPT:

                Return proc translate_math_superscript with translator_ptr, node_ptr
            Otherwise:
                If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_MATH_SUBSCRIPT:

                    Return proc translate_math_subscript with translator_ptr, node_ptr
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Default: translate as regular node
    Return proc translate_node with translator_ptr, node_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Math commands divide into structurally distinct shapes that need
dedicated translators: `\frac{n}{d}` (binary, produces a fraction),
`\sqrt[n]{x}` (radicand with optional degree), big operators like
`\sum`, `\int`, `\prod`, `\lim` (decorated with limits via metadata).
The rest fall through to the generic HIR.HIR_CALL form. Splitting
specialised cases out lets math-backends emit native semantics for
common idioms while still supporting the long tail of math packages.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads command_name from parser offset 8. Cascading string_equals tests:
"\\frac" -> translate_math_frac; "\\sqrt" -> translate_math_sqrt;
"\\sum"/"\\int"/"\\prod"/"\\lim" -> translate_math_operator with
HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUM/INT/PROD/LIMIT respectively. Fallthrough:
allocates 40-byte HIR_CALL node with command_name at offset 8;
translates args_list (parser offset 16) into hir_args; writes at
offset 16. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_command" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, command_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let command_name be proc read_string from Memory with command_ptr, 8

    Note: Translate specific math commands
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\frac":
        Return proc translate_math_frac with translator_ptr, command_ptr
    Otherwise:
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\sqrt":

            Return proc translate_math_sqrt with translator_ptr, command_ptr
        Otherwise:
            If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\sum":

                Return proc translate_math_operator with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUM
            Otherwise:
                If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\int":

                    Return proc translate_math_operator with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_MATH_INT
                Otherwise:
                    If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\prod":

                        Return proc translate_math_operator with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_MATH_PROD
                    Otherwise:
                        If proc string_equals from StringCore with command_name, "\\lim":

                            Return proc translate_math_operator with translator_ptr, command_ptr, HIR_LATEX_MATH_LIMIT
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Generic math command
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 40
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR.HIR_CALL
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, command_name

    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with command_ptr, 16
    Let hir_args be proc translate_argument_list with translator_ptr, args_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, hir_args

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`\frac{n}{d}` has exactly two arguments: numerator and denominator,
positional. We preserve them as separate HIR sub-trees (not strings)
so nested fractions like `\frac{\frac{a}{b}}{c}` translate correctly
with full recursion. Storing at distinct HIR offsets (8 and 16) lets
backends access either side without iterating an arg list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_MATH_FRAC. Reads
args_list from parser offset 16. Gets numerator_arg at index 0,
translates via translate_argument_content, writes at HIR offset 8.
Gets denominator_arg at index 1, translates, writes at offset 16.
Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_frac" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, frac_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR fraction node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_MATH_FRAC

    Note: Extract numerator and denominator
    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with frac_ptr, 16

    Let numerator_arg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, 0
    Let numerator_content be proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, numerator_arg
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, numerator_content

    Let denominator_arg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, 1
    Let denominator_content be proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, denominator_arg
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, denominator_content

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`\sqrt[n]{x}` covers both square root (`\sqrt{x}`, default n=2) and nth
root (`\sqrt[n]{x}`). The [n] is an OPTIONAL bracketed argument that
appears BEFORE the required {x}; we treat its absence as root_degree=0
(meaning "use default sqrt visualisation"). The radicand always comes
as args[0].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_MATH_SQRT. Reads
args_list from parser offset 16. Gets radicand_arg at index 0,
translates via translate_argument_content, writes at HIR offset 8.
Initialises root_degree=0. If get_list_size(args_list) > 1, gets
degree_arg at index 1, translates, assigns to root_degree. Writes
root_degree at HIR offset 16. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_sqrt" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, sqrt_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR square root node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_MATH_SQRT

    Note: Extract radicand
    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with sqrt_ptr, 16
    Let radicand_arg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, 0
    Let radicand_content be proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, radicand_arg
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, radicand_content

    Note: Extract optional root degree (nth root)
    Let root_degree be 0
    Let arg_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with args_list
    If arg_count is greater than 1:
        Let degree_arg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, 1
        Set root_degree to proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, degree_arg
    End If
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, root_degree

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Big operators (`\sum_{i=0}^{n} x_i`, `\int_0^1 f(x) dx`, `\prod`,
`\lim`) carry three semantic pieces: subscript (lower limit / index
binding), superscript (upper limit), and operand (the expression
following the operator). LaTeX's parser attaches subscript/superscript
via the metadata side channel (parser offset 24) because they're
SYNTACTICALLY children of the operator command but APPEAR as
separate `_{...}` and `^{...}` notation. We harvest both from metadata
and translate them as full HIR sub-trees.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 48-byte HIR node tagged with hir_type. Initialises
subscript_ptr=0, superscript_ptr=0. Reads metadata at parser offset 24;
if non-zero: reads has_subscript at metadata offset 0, if non-zero
reads subscript_content at metadata offset 8 and translates via
translate_argument_content into subscript_ptr; reads has_superscript at
metadata offset 16, if non-zero reads superscript_content at metadata
offset 24 and translates into superscript_ptr. Writes subscript_ptr at
HIR offset 8 and superscript_ptr at offset 16. Reads args_list at
parser offset 16; if non-zero and has elements, translates args[0] as
operand_content. Writes operand_content at HIR offset 24. Returns
hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_operator" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, op_ptr as Integer, hir_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR math operator node (sum, integral, product, limit)
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 48
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, hir_type

    Note: Extract subscript (lower limit) and superscript (upper limit) from operator metadata
    Note: In LaTeX, operators like \sum_{lower}^{upper} have subscript/superscript attached
    Let subscript_ptr be 0
    Let superscript_ptr be 0

    Note: Check operator metadata for attached subscript/superscript
    Let metadata be proc read_integer from Memory with op_ptr, 24
    If metadata is not equal to 0:
        Note: Look for subscript marker in metadata
        Let has_subscript be proc read_integer from Memory with metadata, 0
        If has_subscript is not equal to 0:
            Let subscript_content be proc read_integer from Memory with metadata, 8
            Set subscript_ptr to proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, subscript_content
        End If

        Note: Look for superscript marker in metadata
        Let has_superscript be proc read_integer from Memory with metadata, 16
        If has_superscript is not equal to 0:
            Let superscript_content be proc read_integer from Memory with metadata, 24
            Set superscript_ptr to proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, superscript_content
        End If
    End If

    Note: Store translated subscript and superscript in HIR node
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, subscript_ptr
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, superscript_ptr

    Note: Extract operand (what comes after the operator)
    Let args_list be proc read_integer from Memory with op_ptr, 16
    Let operand_content be 0
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with args_list
        If arg_count is greater than 0:
            Let operand_arg be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, 0
            Set operand_content to proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, operand_arg
        End If
    End If
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 24, operand_content

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standalone superscript node (`x^{...}` not attached to a big operator
- those go through translate_math_operator). Content is a math
expression that gets recursively translated through
translate_math_content so nested formulas in the exponent work.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUPERSCRIPT. Reads
content_list from parser offset 8, calls translate_math_content. Writes
the resulting HIR list at offset 8. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_superscript" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, sup_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR superscript node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUPERSCRIPT

    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with sup_ptr, 8
    Let hir_content be proc translate_math_content with translator_ptr, content_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, hir_content

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standalone subscript node (`x_{...}`) - the subscript counterpart to
translate_math_superscript. Same content-walking pattern; only the
HIR type tag differs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUBSCRIPT. Reads
content_list from parser offset 8, calls translate_math_content. Writes
result at HIR offset 8. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_subscript" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, sub_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR subscript node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUBSCRIPT

    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with sub_ptr, 8
    Let hir_content be proc translate_math_content with translator_ptr, content_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 8, hir_content

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
In math mode, text blocks are NOT prose - they're identifiers
representing variables (x, n, alpha) or symbols. We tag them as
HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER so backends emit the math-italic style that
distinguishes math variables from regular text. This is why math-mode
needs a separate text dispatcher from prose text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte HIR node tagged HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER. Reads text
content from parser offset 8 via read_string, writes at HIR offset 8.
Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_math_text" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, text_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Math text (variables, symbols)
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER

    Let text_content be proc read_string from Memory with text_ptr, 8
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, text_content

    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Citation and Reference Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
`\cite[note]{key}` produces a bibliography citation; the key references
an entry in the .bib file. We track each citation in the translator's
citation_table (offset 40) so post-translation passes can verify all
cited keys actually exist in the bibliography and emit "unused
citation" warnings for entries that never appear. The optional note
is preserved for backends that render inline notes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_CITATION. Reads key_arg
from parser offset 8, extracts cite_key, writes at HIR offset 8. Calls
track_citation(translator_ptr, cite_key) to enroll in citation_table.
Reads note_arg at parser offset 16; if non-zero extracts note_text
(else ""), writes at HIR offset 16. Calls add_to_module. Returns
hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_citation" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, cite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR citation node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_CITATION

    Note: Extract citation key
    Let key_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with cite_ptr, 8
    Let cite_key be proc extract_text_from_argument from key_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, cite_key

    Note: Track citation in citation table
    proc track_citation with translator_ptr, cite_key

    Note: Extract optional note
    Let note_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with cite_ptr, 16
    Let note_text be ""
    If note_arg is not equal to 0:
        Set note_text to proc extract_text_from_argument from note_arg
    End If
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 16, note_text

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`\ref{label}` produces a cross-reference that resolves to the label's
counter value (section number, equation number, etc.) at typeset time.
Forward references to labels not yet seen are common, so we verify
existence against the label_table at HIR-build time and emit a warning
(NOT an error) for unknown labels - the user might fix the label
later, and erroring out would block translation entirely.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_REFERENCE. Reads
label_arg from parser offset 8, extracts ref_label, writes at HIR
offset 8. Calls check_label_exists(translator_ptr, ref_label); if 0,
builds warning "Reference to undefined label: <label>" via
string_concat and calls add_warning. Calls add_to_module. Returns
hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_reference" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, ref_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR reference node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_REFERENCE

    Note: Extract reference label
    Let label_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with ref_ptr, 8
    Let ref_label be proc extract_text_from_argument from label_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, ref_label

    Note: Verify label exists in label table
    Let label_exists be proc check_label_exists with translator_ptr, ref_label
    If label_exists is equal to 0:
        Let warning_msg be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Reference to undefined label: ", ref_label
        proc add_warning with translator_ptr, warning_msg
    End If

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
`\label{name}` attaches an anchor to the current location so subsequent
`\ref` calls can resolve to it. We track each label in the
translator's label_table (offset 32) for two reasons: (1) to populate
the cross-reference machinery that translate_reference consults; (2)
to detect duplicate labels which silently break LaTeX's resolution
and need to surface as warnings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte HIR node tagged HIR_LATEX_LABEL. Reads name_arg
from parser offset 8, extracts label_name, writes at HIR offset 8.
Calls track_label(translator_ptr, label_name) which adds it to the
label_table and emits a duplicate-label warning if already present.
Calls add_to_module. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_label" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, label_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR label node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR_LATEX_LABEL

    Note: Extract label name
    Let name_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with label_ptr, 8
    Let label_name be proc extract_text_from_argument from name_arg
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, label_name

    Note: Track label in label table
    proc track_label with translator_ptr, label_name

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: List Item Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
`\item` inside itemize/enumerate/description environments produces one
list entry. Description lists support an optional `[label]` (e.g.
`\item[Foo]` -> labelled "Foo"); itemize and enumerate ignore it but
the parser preserves it anyway. The item body is a list of content
nodes recursively translated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte HIR node tagged HIR.HIR_BLOCK (items render as
nested blocks within their containing list environment). Reads
label_arg from parser offset 8; if non-zero extracts text into
label_text (else ""), writes at HIR offset 8. Reads content_list at
parser offset 16, builds hir_content by looping each child through
translate_node and appending non-zero results. Writes hir_content at
HIR offset 16. Calls add_to_module. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_list_item" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, item_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR list item node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR.HIR_BLOCK

    Note: Extract optional label
    Let label_arg be proc read_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 8
    Let label_text be ""
    If label_arg is not equal to 0:
        Set label_text to proc extract_text_from_argument from label_arg
    End If
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, label_text

    Note: Translate item content
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 16
    Let hir_content be proc create_list from ListCore

    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let content_node be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
            Let hir_content_node be proc translate_node with translator_ptr, content_node
            If hir_content_node is not equal to 0:
                proc add_to_list from ListCore with hir_content, hir_content_node
            End If
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 16, hir_content

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Text Block Translation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Plain text in document body. Stored as HIR.HIR_LITERAL so backends
can output it verbatim (after backend-specific escaping for special
characters in the target format). Note this is the prose-text path;
translate_math_text handles math-mode text differently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte HIR node tagged HIR.HIR_LITERAL. Reads text
content from parser offset 8 via read_string, writes at HIR offset 8.
Calls add_to_module. Returns hir_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_text_block" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, text_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR text literal node
    Let hir_node be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_node, 0, HIR.HIR_LITERAL

    Let text_content be proc read_string from Memory with text_ptr, 8
    proc write_string from Memory with hir_node, 8, text_content

    proc add_to_module with translator_ptr, hir_node

    Return hir_node
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Argument Processing Helpers
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Common helper for translating a list of LaTeX command arguments into
a list of HIR sub-trees. Used by every command translator that takes
multiple args (citations, references, sections, etc.). Returning an
empty list when args_list is null keeps callers' code uniform - no
null-check required at the call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an empty hir_args list via ListCore.create_list. If args_list
is null, returns hir_args (empty). Otherwise loops index 0 to count-1:
reads arg_ptr via ListCore.get_from_list, calls
translate_argument_content, appends result to hir_args. Returns
hir_args.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_argument_list" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, args_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir_args be proc create_list from ListCore

    If args_list is equal to 0:
        Return hir_args
    End If

    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with args_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let arg_ptr be proc get_from_list from ListCore with args_list, index
        Let hir_arg be proc translate_argument_content with translator_ptr, arg_ptr
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with hir_args, hir_arg
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_args
End Process

@Reasoning:
LaTeX command arguments wrap their content in a NODE_ARGUMENT box.
This translator UNWRAPS the box and treats the contained list as a
HIR block. Non-argument nodes (passed accidentally or from edge
cases in the parser) fall through to direct translate_node which is
the safe path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards arg_ptr (returns 0). Reads node_type at offset 0. If NOT
NODE_ARGUMENT, tail-calls translate_node. Otherwise reads
content_list at arg offset 16. If content_list is null, returns 0.
Allocates a 24-byte HIR_BLOCK node. Creates hir_content list. Loops
content_list translating each child via translate_node, appending
non-zero results to hir_content. Writes hir_content at HIR block
offset 8. Returns hir_block.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_argument_content" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If arg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_ARGUMENT:
        Note: Not an argument node, translate directly
        Return proc translate_node with translator_ptr, arg_ptr
    End If

    Note: Extract content from argument
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 16

    If content_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create HIR block to hold argument content
    Let hir_block be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_block, 0, HIR.HIR_BLOCK

    Let hir_content be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let content_node be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
        Let hir_node be proc translate_node with translator_ptr, content_node
        If hir_node is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list from ListCore with hir_content, hir_node
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc write_integer from Memory with hir_block, 8, hir_content

    Return hir_block
End Process

@Reasoning:
String-only extraction from an argument, ignoring nested HIR
structure. Used where the consumer needs a plain string (package
names, section titles, label names, citation keys) rather than full
HIR. Walks all NODE_TEXT_BLOCK children and concatenates their text;
non-text children (nested commands, etc.) are silently skipped
because a string representation of a nested command isn't meaningful.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards arg_ptr (returns ""). Reads node_type at offset 0. If
NOT NODE_ARGUMENT: if it IS NODE_TEXT_BLOCK, returns its text via
read_string at offset 8; otherwise returns "". For NODE_ARGUMENT,
reads content_list at offset 16 (returns "" if null). Loops index
0..count-1: reads content_node, tests its node_type; if it's
NODE_TEXT_BLOCK, reads the text and string_concats it onto result.
Returns the accumulated result.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_text_from_argument" that takes arg_ptr as Integer returns String:
    If arg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_ARGUMENT:
        Note: Try to extract text from other node types
        If node_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_TEXT_BLOCK:
            Return proc read_string from Memory with arg_ptr, 8
        End If
        Return ""
    End If

    Note: Extract content from argument node
    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 16

    If content_list is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Note: Concatenate all text blocks in argument
    Let result be ""
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let content_node be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, index
        Let content_type be proc read_integer from Memory with content_node, 0

        If content_type is equal to LaTeXParser.NODE_TEXT_BLOCK:
            Let text be proc read_string from Memory with content_node, 8
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, text
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Label and Citation Tracking
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Label-table maintenance. Each `\label{name}` must produce a unique
entry - LaTeX silently uses the first definition and ignores
subsequent ones, but we WARN explicitly because this is almost
certainly a user error (typically caused by copy-pasted sections).
We use linear scan rather than a hash because label_tables are
small (dozens to low hundreds per document).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads label_table at translator offset 32. Loops index 0..count-1
comparing each existing_label against label_name via string_equals.
On match, builds warning "Duplicate label: <name>" via string_concat
and calls add_warning, returns 0 (not added). After full loop with
no match, calls ListCore.add_to_list to append label_name. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "track_label" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, label_name as String returns Integer:
    Let label_table be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 32

    Note: Check if label already exists
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with label_table
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let existing_label be proc get_from_list from ListCore with label_table, index
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with existing_label, label_name:
            Note: Duplicate label warning
            Let warning_msg be proc string_concat from StringCore with "Duplicate label: ", label_name
            proc add_warning with translator_ptr, warning_msg
            Return 0
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add new label
    proc add_to_list from ListCore with label_table, label_name

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Label-existence test used by translate_reference to detect forward-
references to labels that never get defined. Linear scan matches
track_label's storage strategy (small list, no hashing). Returns
Integer 0/1 boolean so callers can use simple equality tests.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads label_table at translator offset 32. Loops index 0..count-1
calling string_equals on each existing_label vs label_name. Returns 1
on first match. Returns 0 after exhausting the list with no match.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_label_exists" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, label_name as String returns Integer:
    Let label_table be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 32

    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with label_table
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let existing_label be proc get_from_list from ListCore with label_table, index
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with existing_label, label_name:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Citation-table maintenance. Unlike labels, duplicate citations are
NORMAL and not warned - a single source can be cited many times. We
maintain the table as a set (deduplicating) so downstream cross-
checking against the .bib file can ask "is this key cited at all?"
without inflating counts by citation frequency.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads citation_table at translator offset 40. Loops index 0..count-1
calling string_equals on each existing_key vs cite_key. On match
returns 0 (not added because already present, but NOT a warning).
After full loop without match, calls ListCore.add_to_list to append
cite_key. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "track_citation" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, cite_key as String returns Integer:
    Let citation_table be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 40

    Note: Add citation key if not already present
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with citation_table
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let existing_key be proc get_from_list from ListCore with citation_table, index
        If proc string_equals from StringCore with existing_key, cite_key:
            Note: Already tracked
            Return 0
        End If
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add new citation
    proc add_to_list from ListCore with citation_table, cite_key

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Module Management
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central registration point that every top-level translator calls to
enroll its produced HIR node in the module's items list. Centralising
this means changing the module-storage layout in the future only
touches this one function. Null hir_node is rejected (returns 0)
because callers conventionally pass 0 to indicate "translation
produced nothing" - we don't want zero-entries polluting the items
list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards hir_node (returns 0). Reads module_ptr at translator
offset 0, then items_list at module offset 16. Calls
ListCore.add_to_list to append hir_node. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_to_module" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, hir_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If hir_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let module_ptr be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 0
    Let items_list be proc read_integer from Memory with module_ptr, 16

    proc add_to_list from ListCore with items_list, hir_node

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Error and Warning Handling
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Hard-error reporter. Errors are collected into a list (offset 8 of
translator) rather than aborting on the first one so a single
translation run surfaces every problem the user needs to fix - tools
that re-run on each save become much more useful with this.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads errors_list at translator offset 8. Calls
ListCore.add_to_list(errors_list, message). Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_error" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Let errors_list be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 8
    proc add_to_list from ListCore with errors_list, message
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warning reporter. Warnings differ from errors: they surface
possibly-wrong situations (undefined refs, duplicate labels) but
don't fail translation. Stored at translator offset 16, paralleling
the errors-list pattern.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads warnings_list at translator offset 16. Calls
ListCore.add_to_list(warnings_list, message). Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_warning" that takes translator_ptr as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Let warnings_list be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 16
    proc add_to_list from ListCore with warnings_list, message
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor exposing the errors list to outside code (CLI driver,
test harness, IDE) so it can render diagnostics to the user.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads and returns the errors_list pointer at translator offset 8.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_errors" that takes translator_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public accessor for the warnings list, mirroring get_errors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads and returns the warnings_list pointer at translator offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_warnings" that takes translator_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean predicate exposing whether the last translation produced any
errors. Used by the driver to decide whether to proceed with codegen
(only when has_errors returns 0).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads errors_list at translator offset 8, then count via
ListCore.get_list_size. Returns 1 if count > 0, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "has_errors" that takes translator_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let errors_list be proc read_integer from Memory with translator_ptr, 8
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with errors_list

    If count is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process
